| Moz\u0101re' \n| 4.7.7(2)\n|<ref>Included in 4.7.15.</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"5\" | 5\n| <poem style=\"font-family:monospace;font-size: 120%;margin: -5px 0 -5px 0\">    \u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 </poem>\n| Hazaj \n| 5.1.10 (M)\n|3.2%\n|-\n| <poem style=\"font-family:monospace;font-size: 120%;margin: -5px 0 -5px 0\">    \u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 </poem>\n| Hazaj \n| 5.1.11\n|0.7%\n|-\n| <poem style=\"font-family:monospace;font-size: 120%;margin: -5px 0 -5px 0\">    \u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 </poem>\n| Hazaj \n| 5.1.13 (R)\n|\u2013\n|-\n| <poem style=\"font-family:monospace;font-size: 120%;margin: -5px 0 -5px 0\">      \u2013 u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 </poem>\n| Rajaz \n| 5.2.16\n|0.8%\n|-\n| <poem style=\"font-family:monospace;font-size: 120%;margin: -5px 0 -5px 0\">        u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013\n</poem>\n| Ramal \n| 5.3.16 \n|0.6%\n|-\n|}\n\nPattern 4.1 can be seen as being derived from pattern 3.1 by the reversal (or \"syncopation\"/\"anaclasis\") of the 2nd and 3rd syllables.<ref>Hayes (1979), pp. 210\u20131.</ref>\n\nPattern 5.1 can be seen as being derived from pattern 3.3 by the reversal of the 6th and 7th syllables.\n\n==Catalexis==\nThe final syllable of a line always counts as long because of the pause which follows; so when the line is made [[catalectic]] (that is, it loses its final syllable), the rhythm \u2013 u u at the end of the line automatically changes to \u2013 u \u2013. An example is 3.4.11:\n:| \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\nThe metre 3.4.07(2), which has a pause internally, is catalectic in both halves of the line:\n:| \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 || \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\nThis can be compared with the full version of the same metre, 3.4.16:\n:| \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 |\n\nThe commonly used ''mojtass'' metre (4.1.15) is another catalectic metre, since it is made up of two sections, 8 and 7 syllables long, often with a break between:\n:| u \u2013 u \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 || u \u2013 u \u2013 | <u>u u</u> \u2013 |\n\nIt has been argued that metres can be shortened at the beginning as well as at the end of the line.<ref>Farzaad (1967), pp. 58\u201364.</ref> For example, the ''khaf\u012bf'' metre (4.5.11) is simply the ''mojtass'' (4.1.15) with the first foot removed:\n:| x u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | <u>u u</u> \u2013 |\n\n==Examples of the metres from Persian poets==\nIn the section below, examples are given of some well known poems in various of the above metres. The transliteration is based on that approved by the United Nations in 2012, which represents the current pronunciation of educated speakers in Iran, except that to make scansion easier, the long vowels are marked (\u0101, \u0113, \u012b, \u014d, \u016b).<ref>''[http://unstats.un.org/unsd/geoinfo/UNGEGN/docs/10th-uncsgn-docs/econf/E_CONF.101_118_Rev.1_Transcription%20symbols%20for%20Persian_Updated.pdf New Persian Romanization System. E/CONF.101/118/Rev.1*]''. Tenth United Nations Conference on the Standardization of Geographical Names. New York, 31 July \u2013 9 August 2012.</ref> (See [[Romanization of Persian]].) The glottal stop is written ('). ''x'' = ''kh'' (as in \"Khayy\u0101m\").\n\nTo help with reading the lines, overlong syllables are underlined in the transcriptions below. These are pronounced longer than the usual long syllables\n\n===Pattern 1 (''motaq\u0101reb'')===\nThe first pattern, based on the foot u \u2013 \u2013, is known by the Arabic name ''mutaq\u0101rib'' (''motaq\u0101reb''). It is found in only two metres, 1.1.11 and 1.1.12.<ref>A 9-syllable version exists but is extremely rare: Elwell-Sutton (1976), p. 147.</ref> The first of these is mostly used for ''masnav\u012b'' (rhyming couplet) poems, but also occasionally for monorhyme lyric poems.\n\n====Ferdowsi's ''Shahnameh''====\nThe metre 1.1.11 is one of the earliest to be found in Persian poetry of the Islamic period and is one of the seven metres used to make the long poems known as ''[[masnavi (poetic form)|masnavi]]''. It is most famously used for the 50,000-line epic poem the ''[[Shahnameh]]'' of [[Ferdowsi]], completed c. AD 1010, which begins:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0647 \u0646\u0627\u0645 \u062e\u062f\u0627\u0648\u0646\u062f \u062c\u0627\u0646 \u0648 \u062e\u0631\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06a9\u0632\u06cc\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u062a\u0631 \u0627\u0646\u062f\u06cc\u0634\u0647 \u0628\u0631\u0646\u06af\u0630\u0631\u062f}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|be n\u0101m-\u0113 Xod\u0101vand-e j\u0101n \u014d xerad}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|k-az-\u012bn bartar and\u012b\u0161e bar-na-gzarad}}\n\n:| u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 |\n\n:\"In the name of the Lord of the soul and intellect,\n:since higher than this, thought cannot pass.\"\n\n====Saadi's ''Bustan''====\n[[Saadi Shirazi|Saadi]]'s long poem the [[Bustan (book)|B\u016bst\u0101n]], completed in 1257, is also written in this metre. The first line is as follows:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0647 \u0646\u0627\u0645 \u062e\u062f\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u06a9\u0647 \u062c\u0627\u0646 \u0622\u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0633\u062e\u0646 \u06af\u0641\u062a\u0646 \u0627\u0646\u062f\u0631 \u0632\u0628\u0627\u0646 \u0622\u0641\u0631\u06cc\u062f}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|be n\u0101m-\u0113 Xod\u0101-y\u012b ke j\u0101n \u0101far\u012bd}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|soxan goftan andar zab\u0101n \u0101far\u012bd}}\n\n:| u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 |\n\n:\"In the name of that God who created the soul,\n:who created speaking in the tongue.\"\n\n====''Ban\u012b '\u0100dam''====\n{{see|Bani Adam}}\nThe same metre 1.1.11 can also be used for shorter poems such as Saadi's well-known lines below from the [[Gulistan (book)|Golest\u0101n]],<ref>Golestan 1.10</ref> which are inscribed on a carpet that hangs in the United Nations in New York:<ref>[http://www.payvand.com/news/05/aug/1234.html Payvand News 24 August 2005]</ref>\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0646\u0649\u200c\u0622\u062f\u0645 \u0627\u0639\u0636\u0627\u06cc \u06cc\u06a9 \u067e\u06cc\u06a9\u0631\u0646\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06a9\u0647 \u062f\u0631 \u0622\u0641\u0631\u06cc\u0646\u0634 \u0632 \u06cc\u06a9 \u06af\u0648\u0647\u0631\u0646\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0648 \u0639\u0636\u0648\u0649 \u0628\u0647 \u062f\u0631\u062f \u0622\u0648\u0631\u064e\u062f \u0631\u0648\u0632\u06af\u0627\u0631}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062f\u06af\u0631 \u0639\u0636\u0648\u0647\u0627 \u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0645\u0627\u0646\u064e\u062f \u0642\u0631\u0627\u0631}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062a\u0648 \u06a9\u0632 \u0645\u062d\u0646\u062a \u062f\u06cc\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u06cc\u200c\u063a\u0645\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0646\u0634\u0627\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u0647 \u0646\u0627\u0645\u062a \u0646\u0647\u0646\u062f \u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|ban\u012b-'\u0100dam a'z\u0101-ye yek peykar-and}} <ref>A variant reading is {{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0646\u0649\u200c\u0622\u062f\u0645 \u0627\u0639\u0636\u0627\u06cc \u06cc\u06a9\u062f\u06cc\u06af\u0631\u0646\u062f}} \"The sons of Adam are members of one another\". See [[Bani Adam]].</ref>\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|ke dar '\u0101far\u012bn-e\u0161 ze yek gowhar-and}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u010do \u02beozv-\u012b be dard \u0101varad <u>r\u016bz</u>g\u0101r}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|degar <u>'ozv</u>-h\u0101-r\u0101 na-m\u0101nad qar\u0101r}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|to k-az mehnat-\u0113 d\u012bgar\u0101n b\u012bqam-\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|na-\u0161\u0101yad ke n\u0101m-at nahand \u0101dam\u012b}}\n\n:| u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 |\n\n:\"The sons of Adam are members of one body,\n: since in his creation they are of one essence.\n: when fate brings one member pain\n:the other members are affected.\n:You, who are without sorrow at others' affliction,\n:it is not fitting that they should call you by the name 'human'.\"\n\n===Pattern 2.1 (''hazaj'')===\n====The Shirazi Turk====\n{{see|Shirazi Turk}}\nPattern 2.1, commonly known as ''[[hazaj meter|hazaj]]'', is similar to pattern 1 except that the short syllable is followed not by two but by three long syllables. The metre 2.1.16 is used for the following poem by [[Hafez]]. It has been referred to by [[Michael Craig Hillmann|Michael Hillmann]] as \"the most familiar of Hafez's poems in the English-speaking world\".<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/4310200?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents ''Iranian Studies'', vol 8. (1975), issue 3, p. 164]</ref> As sometimes happens with the longer metres, there is a break in the middle of the line; however, the break is not a complete one, since in some lines an overlong syllable or a word followed by the ''[[ez\u0101fe]]'' suffix (''-e'') continues across the break.\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u06af\u0631 \u0622\u0646 \u062a\u0631\u06a9 \u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0632\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u062f\u0633\u062a \u0622\u0631\u062f \u062f\u0644 \u0645\u0627 \u0631\u0627}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0647 \u062e\u0627\u0644 \u0647\u0646\u062f\u0648\u06cc\u0634 \u0628\u062e\u0634\u0645 \u0633\u0645\u0631\u0642\u0646\u062f \u0648 \u0628\u062e\u0627\u0631\u0627 \u0631\u0627}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|'agar '\u0101n Tork-e \u0160\u012br\u0101z\u012b * be dast \u0101rad del-\u0113 m\u0101-r\u0101}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|be x\u0101l-\u0113 Hendu-ya\u0161 bax\u0161am * Samarqand-\u014d Box\u0101r\u0101-r\u0101}}\n\n:| u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 || u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"If that [[Shiraz|Shirazi]] Turk wins my heart,\n:for his<ref>For the male gender and the Turk cf. [http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/homosexuality-iii \"Homosexuality iii. in Persian Literature\"] (''Encyclopaedia Iranica'')</ref> Indian mole I will give [[Samarkand]] and [[Bukhara]].\"<ref>For a discussion of the hidden astrological and sufi meanings in this ode, see [https://www.academia.edu/7897926/Hafiz_Shirazi_Turk_A_Structuralists_Point_of_View Bashiri (1979)].</ref>\n\n====\"Neither a Christian nor a Jew\"====\n[[Rumi]] uses this same metre in the following ghazal from the ''D\u012bv\u0101n-e Shams'':<ref>R. A. Nicholson, ''Selected Poems from the Divani Shamsi Tabriz''.  [https://archive.org/details/SelectedPoemsFromTheDivaniShamsiTabriz-ReynoldA.Nicholson/page/n89/mode/2up pp. 124\u2013127].</ref>\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0647 \u062a\u062f\u0628\u06cc\u0631 \u0627\u06cc \u0645\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u06a9\u0647 \u0645\u0646 \u062e\u0648\u062f \u0631\u0627 \u0646\u0645\u06cc\u062f\u0627\u0646\u0645}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0646\u0647 \u062a\u0631\u0633\u0627 \u0648 \u06cc\u0647\u0648\u062f\u06cc\u0645 \u0646\u0647 \u06af\u0628\u0631\u0645 \u0646\u0647 \u0645\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0645}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u010de tadb\u012br, ey mosalm\u0101n\u0101n? * ke man xod-r\u0101 nem\u012b-d\u0101nam}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|na tars\u0101 v\u014d yah\u016bd\u012b-yam, * na gabr-am na\u02d0 mosalm\u0101n-am}}\n\n:| u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 || u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"What am I to do, o Muslims? Since I do not know myself;\n:I am not a Christian or a Jew, nor a Zoroastrian, nor a Muslim.\"\n\n====Nezami's ''Khosrow and Shirin''====\nAn eleven-syllable form of this pattern, 2.1.11 (that is, omitting the first foot), is one of the two metres considered appropriate for writing ''masnavi'' poems on the theme of love. Examples include [[Fakhruddin As'ad Gurgani|Fakhruddin Gurgani]]'s ''[[Vis o Ramin]]'', and [[Nizami Ganjavi|Nezami]]'s [[Khosrow and Shirin|''Khusrow o Shirin'']], which begins as follows:\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062e\u062f\u0627\u0648\u0646\u062f\u0627 \u062f\u0631 \u062a\u0648\u0641\u06cc\u0642 \u0628\u06af\u0634\u0627\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0646\u0638\u0627\u0645\u06cc \u0631\u0627 \u0631\u0647 \u062a\u062d\u0642\u06cc\u0642 \u0628\u0646\u0645\u0627\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|Xod\u0101vand\u0101 dar-\u0113 tow<u>f\u012bq</u> beg\u0161\u0101y}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|Nez\u0101m\u012b-r\u0101 rah-\u0113 tah<u>q\u012bq</u> benm\u0101y}}\n\n:| u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"O God, open the door of success;\n:Show Nezami the way of investigation\"\n\n====''Do-bayti''====\nThe same metre 2.1.11, or ''hazaj'', was used from early times in popular poetry, such as the [[do-bayt\u012b]], in which the opening iamb (u \u2013) can sometimes be replaced by \u2013 \u2013 or \u2013 u.<ref>Maling (1973), p. 128.</ref> A ''do bayti'' is a quatrain, but in a different metre from the ''ruba'i''; like the ''ruba'i'' its rhyme scheme is ''aa ba''. The theme of love is evident in examples such as the following by [[Baba Tahir|Baba Taher]]:<ref>Recited at [https://ganjoor.net/babataher/2beytiha/sh3/ Baba Taher Do-bayti 3]. Ganjur website.</ref>\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u06af\u0631 \u06cc\u0627\u0631 \u0645\u0631\u0627 \u062f\u06cc\u062f\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u062e\u0644\u0648\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u06af\u0648 \u0627\u06cc \u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0648\u0641\u0627 \u0627\u06cc \u0628\u06cc\u0645\u0631\u0648\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06af\u0631\u06cc\u0628\u0627\u0646\u0645 \u0632 \u062f\u0633\u062a\u062a \u0686\u0627\u06a9 \u0686\u0627\u06a9\u0648}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0646\u062e\u0648\u0627\u0647\u0645 \u062f\u0648\u062e\u062a \u062a\u0627 \u0631\u0648\u0632 \u0642\u06cc\u0627\u0645\u062a}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|agar y\u0101r-\u0113 ma-r\u0101 d\u012bd\u012b be xalvat}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|beg\u016b 'ey b\u012b-vaf\u0101, 'ey b\u012b-morovvat}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|ger\u012bb\u0101n-am ze dast-at <u>\u010d\u0101k</u> \u010d\u0101k\u016b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|na-x\u0101ham <u>d\u016bxt</u> t\u0101 r\u016bz-\u0113 qiy\u0101mat}}\n\n:| u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"If you see my beloved in private\n:Say, 'O faithless one! O without humanity!\n:My collar has been torn to pieces by your hand;\n:I will not sew it up until the day of resurrection.'\"\n\nFor another example, see the article [[Do-bayti]].\n\n====Googoosh's ''Bridge''====\nThe ''Hazaj'' metre 2.1.11 is still in popular use today, for example in the modern Iranian pop song ''Pol'' (\"Bridge\") by the singer [[Googoosh]], which begins:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u062e\u0648\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u0639\u0635\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0647\u0621 \u0639\u0634\u0642}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06a9\u0645\u06a9 \u06a9\u0646 \u0628\u0633\u062a\u0631\u06cc \u0627\u0632 \u06af\u0644 \u0628\u0633\u0627\u0632\u06cc\u0645}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|bar\u0101-y\u0113 x\u0101b-e ma's\u016bm\u0101ne-y\u0113 'e\u0161q}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|komak kon bestar-\u012b 'az gol bes\u0101z\u012bm}}\n\n:| u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"For the innocent sleep of love\n:Help us build a bed of flowers\"\n\nThe modern version of this metre has some licences compared with the classical one. For example, three of the verses of the song have a short syllable in the third position ( u \u2013 u \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013); and overlong syllables are not observed.<ref>See further Mahdavi Mazdeh (2017) on the metres of modern Persian songs.</ref>\n\n===Pattern 2.3 (''rajaz'')===\n====\"The drum of departure\"====\nA different version of this pattern, 2.3.8(2), known as ''rajaz'', is used by Rumi in the following ''[[ghazal]]''. As with 2.1.8(2) illustrated above, there is a break in the middle of the line:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u06cc \u0639\u0627\u0634\u0642\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u06cc \u0639\u0627\u0634\u0642\u0627\u0646 * \u0647\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0645 \u06a9\u0648\u0686 \u0627\u0633\u062a \u0627\u0632 \u062c\u0647\u0627\u0646}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062f\u0631 \u06af\u0648\u0634 \u062c\u0627\u0646\u0645 \u0645\u06cc \u0631\u0633\u062f * \u0637\u0628\u0644 \u0631\u062d\u06cc\u0644 \u0627\u0632 \u0622\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0646}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|'ey '\u0101\u0161eq\u0101n 'ey '\u0101\u0161eq\u0101n, * heng\u0101m-e k\u016b\u010d ast az jah\u0101n}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|dar g\u016b\u0161-e j\u0101n-am m\u012brasad * tabl-\u0113 rah\u012bl az <u>'\u0101s</u>m\u0101n}}\n\n:| \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 || \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"O lovers, o lovers, it is the time for setting off from the world;\n:into the ear of my soul there comes the drum of departure from heaven.\"\n\nThe division of this metre into four parts, each 8 syllables long, is reminiscent of the ''[[anustubh]]'' or ''[[shloka]]'', the most commonly used metre of Indian poetry.\n\n====A Buddha from Farkhar====\nWith this metre there is frequently an internal rhyme at the mid-point of the line, as in the poem above, or in the following by [[Khwaju Kermani]]:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0634\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0632 \u062a\u0631\u06a9\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0634\u062f\u0647 * \u06a9\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u062a \u0632 \u0641\u0631\u062e\u0627\u0631 \u0622\u0645\u062f\u0647}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u0160\u012b<u>r\u0101z</u> Torkest\u0101n \u0161ode * k'\u0101n bot ze Farx\u0101r \u0101made}}\n\n:| \u2013 \u2013u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 || \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"Shiraz has become [[Afghan Turkestan|Turkistan]] * since that \"Buddha\" has come from [[Farkhar District|Farkhar]]\"\n\nThe statues of Buddha from northern Afghanistan were proverbial for their beauty. It is surmised that the handsome young Turk praised here was the prototype of Hafez's \"Shirazi Turk\" in his poem written a few years later.<ref>Ingenito Domenico (2018).[https://doi.org/10.1080/00210862.2018.1511507 \"Hafez\u2019s \u201cShir\u0101zi Turk\u201d: A Geopoetical Approach\"].</ref>\n\n===Pattern 2.4 (''ramal'')===\n====J\u016by-e M\u016bliy\u0101n====\nThe metre 2.4.11, known as ''ramal'', is used for a famous poem by [[Rudaki]] (9th\u201310th century), one of the earliest recorded in classical Persian. Although this metre is often used for rhyming couplet poems ({{lang|fa-Latn|masnav\u012by\u0101t}}), Rudaki's poem is a [[ghazal]] with the same rhyme throughout. The first couplet is notable for its assonance of ''\u016b ... \u016b ... \u016b'' in the first half, balanced by ''\u0101 ... \u0101 ... \u0101'' in the second:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0648\u06cc \u062c\u0648\u06cc \u0645\u0648\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u0622\u06cc\u062f \u0647\u0645\u06cc\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06cc\u0627\u062f \u06cc\u0627\u0631 \u0645\u0647\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0646 \u0622\u06cc\u062f \u0647\u0645\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u016b-ye j\u016by-\u0113 M\u016bliy\u0101n \u0101yad ham\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|y\u0101d-e y\u0101r-\u0113 mehrab\u0101n \u0101yad ham\u012b}}\n\n: \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013\n\n:\"The scent of the Muliyan stream comes constantly;\n:the memory of my dear friend comes constantly\"\n\nIt is said that when the king, Rudaki's patron [[Nasr II]], heard this poem, he immediately leapt on a horse and rode directly from [[Herat]] to [[Bukhara]].<ref>Browne, E. G. (1908), ''A Literary History of Persia'', vol. 1, p. 17.</ref>\n\n====Attar's ''Conference of the Birds''====\nThe same metre 2.4.11 is used in ''masnavi'' poems, such as [[Attar of Nishapur|Att\u0101r]]'s allegorical Sufi poem ''Manteq-ot-Teyr'' or ''[[Conference of the Birds]]'', completed in AD 1177:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0645\u0631\u062d\u0628\u0627 \u0627\u06cc \u0647\u062f\u0647\u062f \u0647\u0627\u062f\u06cc \u0634\u062f\u0647}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062f\u0631 \u062d\u0642\u06cc\u0642\u062a \u067e\u06cc\u06a9 \u0647\u0631 \u0648\u0627\u062f\u06cc \u0634\u062f\u0647}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|marhab\u0101 'ey hodhod-\u0113 h\u0101d\u012b \u0161ode}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|dar haq\u012bqat peyk-e har v\u0101d\u012b \u0161ode}}\n\n:| \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"Welcome, O hoopoe, who hast been made our guide,\n:who hast been made in truth the messenger of each valley.\"\n\n====Rumi's ''Mystical Masnavi''====\nBecause of its use in mystical poems by Attar, the 11-syllable ''ramal'' became associated particularly with poems on a mystical theme.<ref name=\"Elwell-Sutton 1976, p. 244\"> Elwell-Sutton (1976), p. 244.</ref><ref>Thiesen (1982), p. 129.</ref> The most famous of these was the ''[[Masnavi|Masnavi-e Ma'nav\u012b]]'', or the \"Spiritual Masnavi\", completed in 1273, of [[Rumi|Mowlana Jalal al-Din Rumi]] (better known in Iran as Mowlav\u012b) of about 25,000 couplets, which begins:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0634\u0646\u0648 \u0627\u0632 \u0646\u06cc \u0686\u0648\u0646 \u0634\u06a9\u0627\u06cc\u062a \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u06a9\u0646\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u0632 \u062c\u062f\u0627\u06cc\u06cc\u0647\u0627 \u062d\u06a9\u0627\u06cc\u062a \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u06a9\u0646\u062f}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|be\u0161now az ney \u010d\u016bn \u0161ek\u0101yat m\u012bkonad}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|az jod\u0101\u012bh\u0101 hek\u0101yat m\u012bkonad}}\n\n:| \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"Listen to the reed, how it makes complaint;\n:It tells the story of separations.\"\n\n====Breast brimful of pain====\n{{main|S\u012bne m\u0101l\u0101m\u0101l}}\nThe same 15-syllable ''ramal'' metre, 2.4.15, was used in several poems by Hafez, including the following on a mystical theme:\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0633\u06cc\u0646\u0647 \u0645\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0644 \u062f\u0631\u062f \u0627\u0633\u062a \u0627\u06cc \u062f\u0631\u06cc\u063a\u0627 \u0645\u0631\u0647\u0645\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062f\u0644 \u0632 \u062a\u0646\u0647\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u062c\u0627\u0646 \u0622\u0645\u062f \u062e\u062f\u0627 \u0631\u0627 \u0647\u0645\u062f\u0645\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|s\u012bne m\u0101l\u0101m\u0101l-e dard ast; ey deriq\u0101, marham-\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|del ze tanh\u0101'\u012b be j\u0101n \u0101mad, Xod\u0101-r\u0101, hamdam-\u012b}}\n\n:| \u2013 u \u2013\u00a0\u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:My breast is brimful of pain; alas, a remedy!\n:My heart is dying of loneliness, for God's sake, (send) a companion!\n\n====The Turkish minstrel====\nThe same metre, 2.4.15, is also used in the following ''[[qasida]]'' by the 11th-century poet [[Manuchehri]] in praise of a beautiful minstrel. However, the internal rhymes and word breaks suggest a different division of feet:<ref>Manuchehri, [https://ganjoor.net/manoochehri/divanm/ghaside-ghete/sh39/ qaside 39].</ref> \n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u0622\u0646 \u062a\u0631\u06a9\u06cc \u06a9\u0647 \u0627\u0648 \u0686\u0648\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u0632\u0646\u062f \u0628\u0631 \u0686\u0646\u06af\u060c \u0686\u0646\u06af}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u0632 \u062f\u0644 \u0627\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644 \u0628\u06af\u0631\u06cc\u0632\u062f \u0628\u0647 \u0635\u062f \u0641\u0631\u0633\u0646\u06af\u060c \u0633\u0646\u06af}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u012bni \u0101n Tork-\u012b ke \u016b \u010d\u016bn barzanad bar <u>\u010dang</u> \u010dang}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|az del-\u0113 ab<u>d\u0101l</u> bogr\u012bzad be sad far<u>sang</u> sang?}}\n\n:| \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"Do you see that Turk who, when he places his hand ({{lang|fa-Latn|\u010dang}}) on the harp ({{lang|fa-Latn|\u010dang}}),\n:the stone (which weighs on) the heart of his devotees escapes for a hundred [[league (unit)|leagues]]?\"\n\nThe poem has 31 verses all rhyming in ''-ang'', imitating the sound of a harp.\n\n===Pattern 3===\nPattern 3, based on the rhythm u u \u2013 \u2013. This rhythm is not found in Arabic, and it may well go back to ancient Persian times, since it was associated by the Ancient Greeks with Asia Minor and Persia, and known as ''persicus'' or ''[[Ionic meter|ionicus]]''. It was used for example in the opening chorus of [[Aeschylus]]'s play ''The Persians''.<ref>Thiesen (1982), pp. 132, 263\u20134.</ref>\n\nWhenever a poem begins with u u \u2013 \u2013, the first foot may be replaced by \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 or \u2013u \u2013 \u2013, and in fact this change occurs in about 80% of poems,<ref>Elwell-Sutton (1976), pp. 128\u2013129.</ref> with slight differences from one poet to another.<ref>Heny (1981), p. 161.</ref> It is also quite common for the final u u \u2013 to become \u2013 \u2013, although substitution of a long for two shorts in other places in the line is rare.\n\nPoems of pattern 3, when set to music, are often in three-time rhythm.\n\nBecause the foot used, ''fa'el\u0101ton'', is similar to the ''f\u0101'el\u0101ton'' of pattern 2.4 above, this rhythm is likewise known as ''ramal''. However, to distinguish it from 2.4, it is known as ''ramal-e maxb\u016bn'' (literally \"hemmed ''ramal''&thinsp;\", on the analogy of a tailor shortening a dress by hemming it).<ref>Thiesen (1982), p. 132.</ref>\n\n====\"Cloud and wind\"====\nAn example of 3.1.15 is the following poem, which comes from the introduction to [[Saadi Shirazi|Saadi]]'s [[Gulistan (book)|Golest\u0101n]]:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u0628\u0631 \u0648 \u0628\u0627\u062f \u0648 \u0645\u0647 \u0648 \u062e\u0648\u0631\u0634\u06cc\u062f \u0648 \u0641\u0644\u06a9 \u062f\u0631 \u06a9\u0627\u0631\u0646\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062a\u0627 \u062a\u0648 \u0646\u0627\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u06a9\u0641 \u0622\u0631\u06cc\u0651 \u0648 \u0628\u0647 \u063a\u0641\u0644\u062a \u0646\u062e\u0648\u0631\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0647\u0645\u0647 \u0627\u0632 \u0628\u0647\u0631 \u062a\u0648 \u0633\u0631\u06af\u0634\u062a\u0647 \u0648 \u0641\u0631\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0631}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0634\u0631\u0637 \u0627\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0641 \u0646\u0628\u0627\u0634\u062f \u06a9\u0647 \u062a\u0648 \u0641\u0631\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0646\u0628\u0631\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|abr o b\u0101d \u014d mah o xorsh\u012bd o falak dar k\u0101r-<u>and</u>}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|t\u0101 to n\u0101n-\u012b be kaf \u0101r\u012b yo be qeflat na-xor\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|hame 'az bahr-e to sarga\u0161te vo farm\u0101n-bor<u>d\u0101r</u>}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u0161art-e 'en<u>s\u0101f</u> na-b\u0101\u0161ad ke to farm\u0101n na-bar\u012b}}\n\n:| \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 |\n:| \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 |\n:| u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 |\n:| \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 |\n\n:\"Cloud and wind and moon and sun and firmament are at work\n:so that you may get some bread in your hand and not eat it neglectfully.\n:All for your sake are perplexed and obedient to command;\n:it is not a fair condition that you should not obey the command.\"\n\nThe metre requires the second ''o'' \"and\" in the first line above to be pronounced long. This in effect separates into two groups \"cloud and wind\" on the one hand and the astronomical \"moon and sun and firmament\" on the other. Another adaptation to the metre is Saadi's use of the form {{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0645\u0647}} {{lang|fa-Latn|mah}} for \"moon\" instead of the usual {{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0645\u0627\u0647}} {{lang|fa-Latn|m\u0101h}}.\n\n====\"Wine-flask in hand\"====\n{{main|Zolf-'\u0101\u0161ofte}}\nThe same metre 3.1.15 is found in some of Hafez's ghazals, such as this one:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0632\u0644\u0641 \u0622\u0634\u0641\u062a\u0647 \u0648 \u062e\u0648\u06cc \u06a9\u0631\u062f\u0647 \u0648 \u062e\u0646\u062f\u0627\u0646 \u0644\u0628 \u0648 \u0645\u0633\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0647\u0646 \u0686\u0627\u06a9 \u0648 \u063a\u0632\u0644 \u062e\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0648 \u0635\u0631\u0627\u062d\u06cc \u062f\u0631 \u062f\u0633\u062a}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|<u>zolf</u>-'\u0101\u0161ofte vo xoy-karde vo xand\u0101n-lab o <u>mast</u>}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|<u>p\u012br</u>han-\u010d\u0101k o qazal-x\u0101n o sor\u0101h\u012b dar <u>dast</u>}}\n\n:| x u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 |\n:| x u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"Hair-tousled, perspiring, smiling-lipped, and drunk,\n:shirt torn, singing songs, and wine-flask in hand\"\n\nThe ending u u \u2013 can freely alternate with \u2013 \u2013, as in the metre 4.1.15.\n\n====Turkish national anthem====\nThis metre is also used in formal [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] poetry, for example in the Turkish national anthem, the [[\u0130stikl\u00e2l Mar\u015f\u0131]] written in 1921 by [[Mehmet Akif Ersoy]], though the effect in Turkish is different:\n\n:{{rtl-lang|ota|\u0642\u0648\u0631\u0642\u0645\u0627! \u0633\u0648\u0646\u0645\u0632 \u0628\u0648 \u0634\u0641\u0642\u0644\u0631\u062f\u0647 \u06cc\u0648\u0632\u0646 \u0622\u0644 \u0635\u0627\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0642}}\n:{{rtl-lang|ota|\u0633\u0648\u0646\u0645\u0647 \u062f\u0646 \u06cc\u0648\u0631\u062f\u06cc\u0645\u06ad \u0627\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0646\u062f\u0647 \u062a\u0648\u062a\u0646 \u0627\u06ad \u0635\u0648\u06ad \u0627\u0648\u062c\u0627\u0642}}\n\n:{{lang|tr|Korkma! s\u00f6nmez bu \u015fafaklarda y\u00fczen 'al sancak;}}\n:{{lang|tr|S\u00f6nmeden yurdumun \u00fcst\u00fcnde t\u00fcten 'en son ocak.}}\n\n:| x u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 |\n:| x u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 |\n\n:\"Fear not! for the crimson banner that proudly ripples in this glorious dawn shall not fade,\n:Before the last fiery hearth that is ablaze within my homeland is extinguished.\"\n\nIn Ottoman Turkish, the vowels of native Turkish words are generally treated as short (except by an occasional licence called ''im\u00e2le''),<ref>Thiesen (1982), pp. 219\u2013221.</ref> so long syllables are those closed by a consonant. Persian words scan in the same way as in Persian poetry.\n\nNeither of the tunes composed for the Turkish National Anthem, in 1924 and 1930, follows the metre in any way, however.\n\n====\"Arise and bring fur\"====\nAnother metre of the 3rd pattern is 3.3.14. This is one syllable longer than the {{lang|fa-Latn|roba'i}} metre, and starts in a similar way, but the foot division differs, according to Farzaad.<ref>Farzaad (1967), p. 60.</ref> In this metre there is often a word-break after the sixth syllable, whereas in the {{lang|fa-Latn|roba'i}} it is more often after the 5th. As Farzaad divides it, 3.3.14 is really a variation of 3.1.16, but with the first two syllables omitted.\n\nIn the example below by the 11th-century poet [[Manuchehri]], the two short syllables are kept constant and not replaced by a single long:\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062e\u06cc\u0632\u06cc\u062f \u0648 \u062e\u0632 \u0622\u0631\u06cc\u062f \u06a9\u0647 \u0647\u0646\u06af\u0627\u0645 \u062e\u0632\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0627\u062f \u062e\u0646\u06a9 \u0627\u0632 \u062c\u0627\u0646\u0628 \u062e\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0632\u0645 \u0648\u0632\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062a}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|x\u012bz\u012bd-o xaz \u0101<u>r\u012bd</u> ke heng\u0101m-e xaz\u0101n ast}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u0101d-\u0113 xonok az j\u0101neb-e X\u0101<u>razm</u> vaz\u0101n ast}}\n\n:| \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"Arise and bring fur as autumn is here\n:A cold wind is blowing from the direction of [[Khwarazm]].\"\n\nThe poem is stanzaic, consisting of 35 stanzas of 3 couplets each. For the remainder of the above stanza, see [[Manuchehri]].\n\nWhen the singer [[Giti Pashaei|Giti]] sings this poem to a modern tune, the music is in triple time with the downbeat on the final syllable of the above feet. (See External links below.)\n\n====\"Cup in hand\"====\nThe metre 3.3.07(2) starts in the same way as 3.3.14, but the line is broken into two separate halves. An example is a poem of the 13th-century mystic poet [[Fakhr-al-Din Iraqi|Iraqi]]:<ref>Quoted and translated in Browne, E. G. (1920), ''A Literary History of Persia'', vol. 3, pp. 130\u2013131.</ref> \n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u0632 \u067e\u0631\u062f\u0647 \u0628\u0631\u0648\u0646 \u0622\u0645\u062f \u0633\u0627\u0642\u06cc \u0642\u062f\u062d\u06cc \u062f\u0631 \u062f\u0633\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0647\u0645 \u067e\u0631\u062f\u0647\u0654 \u0645\u0627 \u0628\u062f\u0631\u06cc\u062f\u060c \u0647\u0645 \u062a\u0648\u0628\u0647\u0654 \u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0634\u06a9\u0633\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0646\u0645\u0648\u062f \u0631\u062e \u0632\u06cc\u0628\u0627\u060c \u06af\u0634\u062a\u06cc\u0645 \u0647\u0645\u0647 \u0634\u06cc\u062f\u0627}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0648\u0646 \u0647\u06cc\u0686 \u0646\u0645\u0627\u0646\u062f \u0627\u0632 \u0645\u0627 \u0622\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0631 \u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0646\u0634\u0633\u062a}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|az parde bor\u016bn \u0101mad * s\u0101q\u012b qadah-\u012b dar dast}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|ham parde-ye m\u0101 bedr\u012bd * ham towbe-ye m\u0101 be\u0161kast}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|ben<u>m\u016bd</u> rox-\u0113 z\u012bb\u0101 * ga\u0161<u>t\u012bm</u> ham\u0113 \u0161eyd\u0101}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u010d\u016bn <u>h\u012b\u010d</u> na-m\u0101nd az m\u0101 * \u0101mad bar-e m\u0101 ben\u0161ast}}\n\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013\u00a0\u2013 || \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"From behind the curtain came out the wine-pourer, a cup in hand;\n:He both tore our curtain, and broke our resolution.\n:He showed his beautiful face, we all became insane;\n:When nothing remained of us, he came and sat down beside us.\"\n\nThe opening lines of this poem are imitated in Hafez's ghazals 26 (''[[Zolf-'\u0101\u0161ofte]]'') and 27.<ref>[https://ganjoor.net/hafez/ghazal/sh27/ Ghazal 27].</ref>\n\n====\"Drunk without wine\"====\nBased on the pattern \u2013 u u \u2013 (which the Ancient Greeks knew as a ''choriamb'') is the metre 3.4.11, which is found in the following poem by Rumi. Theoretically the pattern, when 11 syllables long, would require the ending \u2013 u u, but since the last syllable of a line always counts as long, the ending becomes \u2013 u \u2013:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0645\u0631\u062f \u062e\u062f\u0627 \u0645\u0633\u062a \u0628\u0648\u062f \u0628\u06cc \u0634\u0631\u0627\u0628}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0645\u0631\u062f \u062e\u062f\u0627 \u0633\u06cc\u0631 \u0628\u0648\u062f \u0628\u06cc \u06a9\u0628\u0627\u0628}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|mard-e Xod\u0101 <u>mast</u> bovad b\u012b \u0161ar\u0101b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|mard-e Xod\u0101 <u>s\u012br</u> bovad b\u012b kab\u0101b}}\n\n:| \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013u u \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"The man of God is intoxicated without wine;\n:the man of God is satisfied without meat.\"\n\n====\"Whoever sees a sweetheart\"====\nThe following metre, 3.4.7(2) consists of the first seven syllables of the above metre repeated. It could also be classified as 4.4.7(2).<ref>Hayes (1979), p. 214</ref> It is exemplified by the following ''[[ghazal]]'' (love poem) by Saadi:\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0647\u0631 \u06a9\u0647 \u062f\u0644\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u062f\u06cc\u062f*  \u0627\u0632 \u062f\u0644\u0634 \u0622\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0641\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0634\u0645 \u0646\u062f\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062e\u0644\u0627\u0635 * \u0647\u0631 \u06a9\u0647 \u062f\u0631 \u0627\u06cc\u0646 \u062f\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0641\u062a}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|har ke del\u0101<u>r\u0101m</u> d\u012bd * az del-a\u0161 \u0101<u>r\u0101m</u> raft}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|<u>\u010da\u0161m</u> nad\u0101rad xa<u>l\u0101s</u> * har ke dar \u012bn <u>d\u0101m</u> raft}}\n\n:| \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 || \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"Whoever sees a sweetheart, from his heart peace disappears.\n:His eye has no release, whoever has fallen into this trap.\"\n\nThe second syllable of {{lang|fa-Latn|xa<u>l\u0101s</u>}}, which comes just before the break in the middle of the verse, is overlong, but just as if it came at the end of a verse, it is scanned simply as long.\n\nVery occasionally in early poets such as [[Rudaki]], the foot | u \u2013 u \u2013 | may be substituted for | \u2013 u u \u2013 | in this metre, as in the ''ruba'i''.<ref>See Thiesen (1982), pp. 100, 153 for examples.</ref>\n\n===Pattern 4===\n====\"Tongue cut out\"====\nOne of the most common<ref name=\"Elwell-Sutton 1976, p. 162\"/> lyric metres is 4.1.15, known as ''mojtass''. It is the 3rd most common metre in Saadi's [[Gulistan (book)|Golest\u0101n]], accounting for 77 short poems.<ref>Thiesen (1982), p. 261.</ref> An example is the following:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0632\u0628\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u06cc\u062f\u0647 \u0628\u06a9\u0646\u062c\u06cc \u0646\u0634\u0633\u062a\u0647 \u0635\u0645\u064c\u0651 \u0628\u06a9\u0645\u064c}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0647 \u0627\u0632 \u06a9\u0633\u06cc \u06a9\u0647 \u0646\u0628\u0627\u0634\u062f \u0632\u0628\u0627\u0646\u0634 \u0627\u0646\u062f\u0631 \u062d\u06a9\u0645}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|zab\u0101n-bor\u012bde be konj-\u012b ne\u0161aste sommon bokm}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|beh az kas-\u012b ke nab\u0101\u0161ad zab\u0101n-a\u0161 'andar hokm}}\n\n:| u \u2013 u \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 || u \u2013 u \u2013 | <u>u u</u> \u2013 |\n\n:\"A person sitting in a corner with his tongue cut out, deaf and dumb,\"\n:is better than one whose tongue is not in control.\"\n\nIn this metre, as in the similar metre 3.1.15, the final u u \u2013 can be replaced by \u2013 \u2013. In poems like the above, there is often a word-break in the middle of the half-line at the point marked ||.\n\n====\"A red rose has bloomed\"====\nThe metre 4.1.15 is also used by [[Hafez]] in 118 poems,<ref>Listed by Thiesen (1982), p. 147.</ref> or 24% of his output. It is exemplified by the well-known [[ghazal]] which begins with this line:\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0634\u06a9\u0641\u062a\u0647 \u0634\u062f \u06af\u0644 \u062d\u0645\u0631\u0627 \u0648 \u06af\u0634\u062a \u0628\u0644\u0628\u0644 \u0645\u0633\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0635\u0644\u0627\u06cc \u0633\u0631\u062e\u0648\u0634\u06cc \u0627\u06cc \u0635\u0648\u0641\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0627\u062f\u0647 \u067e\u0631\u0633\u062a}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u0161ekofte \u0161od gol-e hamr\u0101 vo <u>ga\u0161t</u> bolbol mast}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|sal\u0101-ye sarxo\u0161i ey s\u016bfiy\u0101n-e b\u0101de-parast}}\n\n:| u \u2013 u \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 \u2013 |\n:| u \u2013 u \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | u u \u2013 |\n\n:\"A red rose has bloomed and the nightingale has become intoxicated:\n:it is the call to enjoyment of pleasure, o [[Sufism|Sufis]], worshippers of wine!\"\n\nIn the second line above there is no word break in the middle of the line, but the words flow continuously without a pause. The last syllable of {{lang|fa-Latn|sarxo\u0161i}} is short, because of the following vowel. The last syllable of each line is theoretically overlong, but in the metre it counts simply as long.\n\n====\"Toil and tribulation of the world\"====\nAnother metre of pattern 4 is 4.4.13, named after the Arabic ''munsari\u1e25'' ( x \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 x \u2013 u | \u2013 u u \u2013 ) but not closely resembling it. This was used in this short poem by [[Nasir Khusraw|Naser Khosrow]] to complete his ''[[Safarnama|Safarn\u0101me]]'', the account of his seven-year journey to Mecca, in 1052:\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0631\u0646\u062c \u0648 \u0639\u0646\u0627\u06cc \u062c\u0647\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u06af\u0631\u0686\u0647 \u062f\u0631\u0627\u0632\u0633\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0627 \u0628\u062f \u0648 \u0628\u0627 \u0646\u06cc\u06a9 \u0628\u06cc \u06af\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0647 \u0633\u0631\u0622\u06cc\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0631\u062e \u0645\u0633\u0627\u0641\u0631 \u0632\u0628\u0647\u0631 \u0645\u0627\u0633\u062a \u0634\u0628 \u0648 \u0631\u0648\u0632}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0647\u0631\u0686\u0647 \u06cc\u06a9\u06cc \u0631\u0641\u062a \u0628\u0631 \u0627\u062b\u0631 \u062f\u06af\u0631 \u0622\u06cc\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0645\u0627 \u0633\u0641\u0631 \u0628\u0631\u06af\u0630\u0634\u062a\u0646\u06cc \u06af\u0630\u0631\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0645}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062a\u0627 \u0633\u0641\u0631 \u0646\u0627\u06af\u0630\u0634\u062a\u0646\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u062f\u0631\u0622\u06cc\u062f}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|ranj o 'an\u0101-y\u0113 jah\u0101n 'agar-\u010de dar\u0101z ast}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u0101 bad o b\u0101 <u>n\u012bk</u> b\u012b gom\u0101n be sar \u0101yad}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|<u>\u010darx</u> mos\u0101fer ze bahr-e <u>m\u0101-st</u> \u0161ab \u014d r\u016bz}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|har \u010de yek-\u012b <u>raft</u> bar 'asar degar \u0101yad}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|m\u0101 safar-\u0113 bar-goza\u0161tan\u012b gozar\u0101n\u012bm}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|t\u0101 safar-\u0113 n\u0101-goza\u0161tan\u012b be dar \u0101yad}}\n\n: \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"Although the tribulation and toil of the world is long,\n:with bad and with good without doubt it comes to an end.\n:The wheel is travelling for us night and day;\n:each time one person goes, in his footsteps comes another.\n:We are passing through the journey that must be passed,\n:until the journey which will never end begins.\"\n\nThe monosyllabic start of each half-line and the other word divisions in this poem suggest foot-divisions as marked above.<ref>Farzaad (1967), p. 58.</ref>\n\n====Nez\u0101m\u012b's ''Seven Portraits''====\nThe metre 4.5.11, known as ''khaf\u012bf'', is used for ''masnavi'' writing (long poems in rhyming couplets). One such ''masnavi'' is the 12th-century Nezami's ''[[Haft Paykar]]'' (''Seven Portraits'' or ''Seven Beauties''), which begins as is customary with an address to God:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u06cc \u062c\u0647\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u06cc\u062f\u0647 \u0628\u0648\u062f \u062e\u0648\u06cc\u0634 \u0627\u0632 \u062a\u0648}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0647\u06cc\u0686 \u0628\u0648\u062f\u06cc \u0646\u0628\u0648\u062f\u0647 \u067e\u06cc\u0634 \u0627\u0632 \u062a\u0648}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|'ey jah\u0101n d\u012bde <u>b\u016bd</u> x\u012b\u0161 az t\u014d}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|<u>h\u012b\u010d</u> b\u016bd\u012b na-b\u016bde p\u012b\u0161 az t\u014d}}\n\n:| x u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | <u>u u</u> \u2013 |\n\n:\"O You from whom the world gained its existence;\n:nothing that exists existed earlier than You.\"\n\nAs with other metres ending with (u u \u2013), this is easily changed to (\u2013 \u2013), as in the above couplet.\n\n====\"Every moment a breath\"====\nAnother poet who often used 4.5.11 was [[Saadi Shirazi|Saadi]], and in fact this is the most commonly used metre in his [[Gulistan (book)|Golest\u0101n]], occurring in 159 of the short poems contained in that work, more than twice as many as any other metre.<ref>Thiesen (1982), p. 261.</ref> The introduction to the Golest\u0101n includes a short 12-couplet ''masnavi'' of philosophical reflection, which begins as follows:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0647\u0631 \u062f\u0645 \u0627\u0632 \u0639\u0645\u0631 \u0645\u06cc \u0631\u0648\u062f \u0646\u0641\u0633\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0648\u0646 \u0646\u06af\u0647 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u06a9\u0646\u0645 \u0646\u0645\u0627\u0646\u062f\u0647 \u0628\u0633\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u06cc \u06a9\u0647 \u067e\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0647 \u0631\u0641\u062a \u0648 \u062f\u0631 \u062e\u0648\u0627\u0628\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0645\u06af\u0631 \u0627\u06cc\u0646 \u067e\u0646\u062c \u0631\u0648\u0632 \u062f\u0631\u06cc\u0627\u0628\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|har dam az <u>\u02beomr</u> m\u012b-ravad nafas-\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u010d\u016bn negah m\u012b-konam, na-m\u0101nde bas-\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|'ey ke pan<u>j\u0101h</u> raft-o dar x\u0101b-\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|magar \u012bn <u>panj</u> <u>r\u016bz</u> dar-y\u0101b\u012b?}}\n\n:| x u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | <u>u u</u> \u2013 |\n\n:\"Every moment a breath goes from my life;\n:when I look, not enough has remained.\n:O you for whom fifty has passed and you are still asleep;\n:do you think you will find the answer in these five days?\"\n\nIt includes the famous advice:\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0631\u06af \u0639\u06cc\u0634\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u06af\u0648\u0631 \u062e\u0648\u06cc\u0634 \u0641\u0631\u0633\u062a}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06a9\u0633 \u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f \u0632 \u067e\u0633 \u0632 \u067e\u06cc\u0634 \u0641\u0631\u0633\u062a}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|barg-e 'ey\u0161-\u012b be g\u016br-e <u>x\u012b\u0161</u> fe<u>rest</u>}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|kas nay-\u0101rad ze pas, ze <u>p\u012b\u0161</u> fe<u>rest</u>}}\n\n:\"Send sustenance for the afterlife to your own grave;\n:no one will bring it later, send it in advance.\"\n\n====\"This rose-garden\"====\nIn the same metre 4.5.11 is this well-known poem also from the introduction to the [[Gulistan (book)|Golest\u0101n]]:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0647 \u0686\u0647 \u06a9\u0627\u0631 \u0622\u06cc\u062f\u062a \u0632 \u06af\u0644 \u0637\u0628\u0642\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u0632 \u06af\u0644\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0646 \u0628\u0628\u0631 \u0648\u0631\u0642\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06af\u0644 \u0647\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u067e\u0646\u062c \u0631\u0648\u0632 \u0648 \u0634\u0634 \u0628\u0627\u0634\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0648\u06cc\u0646 \u06af\u0644\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0647\u0645\u06cc\u0634\u0647 \u062e\u0648\u0634 \u0628\u0627\u0634\u062f}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|be \u010de k\u0101r \u0101yad-at ze gol tabaq-\u012b?}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|az golest\u0101n-e man bebar varaq-\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|gol ham\u012bn <u>panj</u> r\u016bz-o \u0161e\u0161 b\u0101\u0161ad}} (or: {{lang|fa-Latn|<u>r\u016bz</u> panj}})\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|v-\u012bn golest\u0101n ham\u012b\u0161e xo\u0161 b\u0101\u0161ad}}\n\n:| x u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | <u>u u</u> \u2013 |\n\n:\"What use to you is a bowl of flowers?\n:Carry away a leaf from my Golestan (flower garden)!\n:A flower lasts only for these five or six days,\n:But this flower-garden is delightful for ever.\"\n\n====A caravan of robes====\nAn example of 4.7.14 is a [[qasida]], by the 10th/11th-century poet [[Farrukhi_Sistani|Farrokhi]] of [[Sistan]], which begins as follows:<ref>For the story of this poem, see Browne (1908 ff), vol. 2, pp. 124\u2013128.</ref>\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0627 \u06a9\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u062d\u064f\u0644\u0651\u0647 \u0628\u0631\u0641\u062a\u0645 \u0632 \u0633\u06cc\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0627 \u062d\u064f\u0644\u0651\u0647\u0654 \u062a\u0646\u06cc\u062f\u0647 \u0632 \u062f\u0644\u060c \u0628\u0627\u0641\u062a\u0647 \u0632 \u062c\u0627\u0646}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u0101 <u>k\u0101r</u>v\u0101n-e holle beraftam ze <u>S\u012bs</u>t\u0101n}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u0101 holle-\u012b tan\u012bde ze del, <u>b\u0101f</u>t\u0113 ze j\u0101n}}\n\n:| \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"With a [[caravan (travellers)|caravan]] of robes I departed from [[Sistan]],\n:with a robe spun from the heart, woven from the soul\"\n\nIn the second line, the perfect suffix ''-e'' is short in {{lang|fa-Latn|tan\u012bde}} \"spun\", but lengthened in {{lang|fa-Latn|b\u0101ft\u0113}} \"woven\".<ref>cf. Thiessen (1982), p. 28.</ref>\n\nThe foot divisions above are given according to Farzaad.<ref>Farzaad (1967), p. 60.</ref>\n\n====Sufi, come!====\nThe same metre, 4.7.14, known as ''moz\u0101re<nowiki>'</nowiki>'', is used in 75 (14%) of Hafez's poems.<ref>Elwell-Sutton (1975), p. 75.</ref><ref>The poems are listed in Thiesen (1982), p. 153.</ref> A well-known example is the following, playing on the words {{lang|fa-Latn|s\u016bf\u012b}} \"[[Sufism|Sufi]]\" and {{lang|fa-Latn|s\u0101f\u012b}} \"clear\":\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0635\u0648\u0641\u06cc \u0628\u06cc\u0627 \u06a9\u0647 \u0622\u06cc\u0646\u0647 \u0635\u0627\u0641\u06cc\u0633\u062a \u062c\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0627}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062a\u0627 \u0628\u0646\u06af\u0631\u06cc \u0635\u0641\u0627\u06cc \u0645\u06cc \u0644\u0639\u0644 \u0641\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0627}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|s\u016bf\u012b biy\u0101, ke \u0101yene s\u0101<u>f\u012b-st</u> <u>j\u0101m</u>-r\u0101}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|t\u0101 bengar\u012b saf\u0101-ye mey-\u0113 <u>la'l</u>-<u>f\u0101m</u>-r\u0101}}\n\n:| \u2013 \u2013\u00a0| u \u2013 u \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"O Sufi, come! Since the cup's mirror is clear;\n:so that you may see the clarity of the ruby-coloured wine.\"\n\n====That black-eyed gazelle====\nThe metre 4.7.7(2) consists of the first seven syllables of 4.7.15 repeated.<ref>Thiesen (1982), p. 157.</ref> The seventh syllable, which is short in the pattern, becomes long because of the pause between the two halves of the line. In this poem, Hafez laments the unfaithfulness of his beloved:<ref>[https://ganjoor.net/hafez/ghazal/sh425/ Hafez ghazal 425.]</ref>\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0622\u0646 \u0622\u0647\u0648\u06cc \u0633\u06cc\u0647 \u0686\u0634\u0645 * \u0627\u0632 \u062f\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0631\u0648\u0646 \u0634\u062f}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0686\u0647 \u0686\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0633\u0627\u0632\u0645 * \u0628\u0627 \u0627\u06cc\u0646 \u062f\u0644 \u0631\u0645\u06cc\u062f\u0647}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u0101n \u0101hu-y\u0113 siyah \u010da\u0161m * az d\u0101m-e m\u0101 bor\u016bn \u0161od}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|y\u0101r\u0101n, \u010de \u010d\u0101re s\u0101zam * b\u0101 \u012bn del-\u0113 ram\u012bde?}}\n\n:| \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 || \u2013 \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"That black-eyed gazelle has escaped from my snare!\n:Friends! What remedy can I find for my troubled heart?\"\n\n===Pattern 5===\n====Nezami's ''Leyli and Majnun''====\nExcept for the ''rub\u0101'\u012b'' metre (see below), pattern 5 is much less commonly found than patterns 3 and 4.<ref>Elwell-Sutton (1976), p. 162; Hayes (1979), p. 222; Deo & Kiparsky, p. 7</ref> The most common is 5.1.10. This is used for ''masnavi'' writing, such as [[Nizami Ganjavi|Nezami]]'s story of Leyli<ref>The pronunciation \"Leyli\" is used in Persian, as Nezami's rhymes show.</ref> and Majnun (completed 1192), which begins as follows, with a play on the words ''n\u0101m'' (name) and ''n\u0101me'' (account or story):\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u06cc \u0646\u0627\u0645 \u062a\u0648 \u0628\u0647\u062a\u0631\u06cc\u0646 \u0633\u0631\u0622\u063a\u0627\u0632}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u06cc\u200c\u0646\u0627\u0645 \u062a\u0648 \u0646\u0627\u0645\u0647 \u06a9\u06cc \u06a9\u0646\u0645 \u0628\u0627\u0632}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|'ey n\u0101m-e to behtar\u012bn sar\u0101q\u0101z}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u012b-n\u0101m-e to n\u0101me key konam b\u0101z?}}\n\n:\u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013\n\n:\"O you whose name is the best beginning;\n:without your name when shall I begin a story?\"\n\nUnlike the other ''masnavi'' metres, which all have eleven syllables, this one has only ten.\n\nThe divisions into feet are unclear. Farzaad proposed the following, using a 5-syllable foot:<ref>Farzaad (1967), p. 60,</ref>\n:\u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 u \u2013 | u \u2013 \u2013\n\n====\"A shirt of leaves\"====\nA shorter example of a ''masnavi'' in 5.1.10, consisting of just three couplets, is found in Saadi's [[Gulistan (book)|Golest\u00e2n]]. It begins:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u067e\u06cc\u0631\u0627\u0647\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u06af \u0628\u0631 \u062f\u0631\u062e\u062a\u0627\u0646}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0648\u0646 \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0647 \u0639\u06cc\u062f \u0646\u06cc\u06a9\u0628\u062e\u062a\u0627\u0646}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|p\u012br\u0101han-e <u>barg</u> bar deraxt\u0101n}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u010dun j\u0101me-ye '\u012bd-e <u>n\u012bk</u>-baxt\u0101n}}\n\n:\u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013\n\n:\"A shirt of leaves on the trees;\n:like the festival clothes of fortunate people.\"\n\n====\"Make haste\"====\nThis metre 5.1.10 is also used, although less often, in lyric poetry. In one of his ghazals, [[Saadi Shirazi|Saadi]] uses it in a stanzaic form with four lines to a verse.<ref>Saadi, [https://ganjoor.net/saadi/divan/ghazals/sh52/ ghazal 52] (Ganjoor).</ref> The rhyme scheme is ''aaba, ccca, ddda'', and so on. The twelfth verse goes as follows:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0633\u062a \u063a\u0631\u0648\u0631 \u0632\u0646\u062f\u06af\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0633\u062a \u0644\u0648\u0627\u0645\u0639 \u062c\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u062f\u0631\u06cc\u0627\u0628 \u062f\u0645\u06cc \u06a9\u0647 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0634\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u06a9\u0647 \u0639\u0645\u0631 \u062f\u0631 \u0634\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0633\u062a}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u0101d <u>ast</u> qor\u016br-e zendeg\u0101n\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|barq <u>ast</u> lav\u0101me'-\u0113 jav\u0101n\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|dar<u>y\u0101b</u> dam-\u012b ke m\u012btav\u0101n\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|be\u0161<u>t\u0101b</u> ke <u>'omr</u> dar \u0161et\u0101b ast}}\n\n: \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013\n\n:\"The vainglory of life is wind;\n:the brilliances of youth are lightning;\n:find a moment when you are able;\n:make haste, since life is in haste.\"\n\nThe internal rhymes ''-dast/-qast, -y\u0101b/-t\u0101b'' confirm Farzaad's claim that a foot division should be made after the first two syllables.\n\n====\"If looking is a sin\"====\nAnother metre using the fifth pattern is 5.3.08(2). Contrary to the practice in other metres which start with a double short, in this metre the initial pair of short syllables (u u) is never replaced by long-short (\u2013 u).<ref>Elwell-Sutton (1976), p. 137.</ref> The metre can be analysed as 5.1.10 without the first two syllables, doubled. There is a break in the middle of each hemistich, but an overlong syllable may overlap the break, as in the first hemistich below, from a ghazal of Saadi:<ref>[http://ganjoor.net/saadi/divan/ghazals/sh391/ Ganjoor].</ref>\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0645\u0646 \u0627\u06af\u0631 \u0646\u0638\u0631 \u062d\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0633\u062a * \u0628\u0633\u06cc \u06af\u0646\u0627\u0647 \u062f\u0627\u0631\u0645}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0647 \u06a9\u0646\u0645 \u0646\u0645\u06cc\u200c\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0646\u0645 * \u06a9\u0647 \u0646\u0638\u0631 \u0646\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u062f\u0627\u0631\u0645}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|man agar nazar har\u0101m <u>ast</u> * bas-\u012b go<u>n\u0101h</u> d\u0101ram}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u010de konam? nem\u012btav\u0101nam * ke nazar ne<u>g\u0101h</u> d\u0101ram}}\n\n:| u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 || u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"If looking is forbidden, I have sinned a lot.\n:What am I to do? I can't stop looking.\"\n\nIt has been suggested that this metre is derived from 3.1.08(2) by the reversal (syncopation or anaclasis) of syllables 4 and 5:<ref>Hayes (1979), pp. 210\u20131.</ref>\n:| u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 || u u \u2013 \u2013 | u u \u2013 \u2013 | (3.1.08(2))\n\nIn Ancient Greek poetry the rhythm (u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013) is known as an [[Anacreontics|anacreontic]], which is named after [[Anacreon]], a poet of Asia Minor (6th\u20135th century BC). In exactly the same way, metricians have suggested that the anacreontic may be derived by anaclasis from an ionic dimeter (u u \u2013 \u2013 u u \u2013 \u2013).<ref>M. L. West, ''Greek Metre'' (Oxford: OUP, 1982), p. 31.</ref>\n\n====\"Tonight you are ours!\"====\nThe same doubled metre 5.3.08(2) is used in a poem by Saadi's contemporary, Rumi:<ref>[https://ganjoor.net/moulavi/shams/ghazalsh/sh2839/ Rumi, Divan-e Shams, ghazal 2839.]</ref>\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u06a9\u0634\u06cc\u062f \u06cc\u0627\u0631 \u06af\u0648\u0634\u0645 * \u06a9\u0647 \u062a\u0648 \u0627\u0645\u0634\u0628 \u0622\u0646 \u0645\u0627\u06cc\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0635\u0646\u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0644\u06cc \u0648\u0644\u06cc\u06a9\u0646 * \u062a\u0648 \u0646\u0634\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u062f\u0647 \u06a9\u062c\u0627\u06cc\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|beke<u>\u0161\u012bd</u> <u>y\u0101r</u> g\u016b\u0161-am * ke to em\u0161ab \u0101n-e m\u0101-\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|sanam\u0101! bal\u012b va-l\u012bkan * to ne\u0161\u0101n bedeh koj\u0101-\u012b}}\n\n:| u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 || u u \u2013 u \u2013 u \u2013 \u2013 |\n\n:\"My beloved pulled my ear, saying 'Tonight you are ours'!\n:\"My idol! Willingly! But you must give some indication of where you are!\"\n\nFor a recording of this poem in Persian see External links.\n\n===''Ruba'i''===\nThe [[ruba'i]] (or {{lang|fa-Latn|rob\u0101'\u012b}}) is unusual in that two metres, 5.1.13 and 3.3.13, are used and are often mixed together in the same poem. It is also unusual in that this combined metre is only used for {{lang|fa-Latn|rob\u0101'\u012by\u0101t}} and not for other types of poem. In fact the two metres are the same except that the 6th and 7th syllables are reversed. The rhythm is therefore the following:\n\n: \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 || u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013\u00a0<u>u u</u> \u2013 | or\n: \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 || \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013\u00a0<u>u u</u> \u2013 |\n\nThe foot divisions are those suggested by Farzaad.<ref>Farzaad (1967), p. 113; cf. Thiesen (1982), p. 167.</ref> At the point marked ||, which Farzaad calls the \"hinge\" of the line, in some kinds of traditional recitation there is often a pause.<ref>See External links, Tajik girls.</ref><ref>cf. also Heny (1981).</ref>\n\nThe metre 5.1.13 is more common than 3.3.13; in an extensive survey of quatrains by Khayyam and Hafez, Farzaad found 70% of lines were in 5.1.13.<ref>Farzaad (1942), p. 70.</ref><ref>See Elwell-Sutton (1976), p. 135 for statistics; in his slightly smaller survey he found 60% were in 5.1.13.</ref> 21% of 100 quatrains examined by Elwell-Sutton were entirely in 5.1.13, but only 8% entirely in 3.3.13. The rest were mixed. \n\nThe ending u u \u2013 is changed to \u2013 \u2013 in nearly half of all verses. Substitution of \u2013 for u u in syllables 3 and 4 is much less common; it occurs in only 5% of lines according to Farzaad.<ref>Farzaad (1942), p. 68.</ref><ref>Elwell-Sutton (1976), p. 134.</ref> (In theory the substitution of \u2013 for u u may also occur in syllables 7 and 8, but this is exceedingly rare.) The most common variant of all, accounting for some 38% of lines,<ref>Farzaad (1942), p. 68.</ref> is:\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 || u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 |\n\n====\"You are drunk!\"====\nAn example of 3.3.13 mixed with 5.1.13 is the following. It is attributed to [[Omar Khayyam]]:<ref>[https://ganjoor.net/khayyam/tarane/tkh6/sh13/ Khayyam, Roba'i 86] (with recording).</ref>\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0634\u06cc\u062e\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u0632\u0646\u06cc \u0641\u0627\u062d\u0634\u0647 \u06af\u0641\u062a\u0627 \u0645\u0633\u062a\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0647\u0631 \u0644\u062d\u0638\u0647 \u0628\u0647 \u062f\u0627\u0645 \u062f\u06af\u0631\u06cc \u067e\u0627\u0628\u0633\u062a\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06af\u0641\u062a\u0627 \u0634\u06cc\u062e\u0627\u060c \u0647\u0631 \u0622\u0646\u200c\u0686\u0647 \u06af\u0648\u06cc\u06cc \u0647\u0633\u062a\u0645}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0622\u06cc\u0627 \u062a\u0648 \u0686\u0646\u0627\u0646\u200c\u06a9\u0647 \u0645\u06cc\u200c\u0646\u0645\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0647\u0633\u062a\u06cc\u061f}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u0161eyx-\u012b be zan-\u012b f\u0101he\u0161e goft\u0101 mast\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|har lahze be d\u0101m-\u0113 degar\u012b p\u0101 bast\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|goft\u0101, \u0161eyx\u0101, har \u0101n\u010de g\u016b'\u012b hastam}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u0101y\u0101 to \u010den\u0101n ke m\u012bnam\u0101'\u012b hast\u012b?}}\n\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | (3.3.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | (3.3.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | (5.1.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | (5.1.13)\n\n:\"A religious leader said to a prostitute 'You are drunk!\n:Every moment you trap your foot in another man's snare.'\n:She said, 'Sir, I am everything that you say.\n:But are ''you'' such a person as you pretend to be?'\"\n\n====\"O friend, come!\"====\nAnother example is the following, also attributed to Khayyam:<ref>[https://ganjoor.net/khayyam/robaee/sh121/ Khayyam, Roba'i 121] (with recording).</ref>\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0627\u06cc \u062f\u0648\u0633\u062a \u0628\u06cc\u0627 \u062a\u0627 \u063a\u0645 \u0641\u0631\u062f\u0627 \u0646\u062e\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u0645}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0648\u06cc\u0646 \u06cc\u06a9\u062f\u0645 \u0639\u0645\u0631 \u0631\u0627 \u063a\u0646\u06cc\u0645\u062a \u0634\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u0645}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0641\u0631\u062f\u0627 \u06a9\u0647 \u0627\u0632\u06cc\u0646 \u062f\u06cc\u0631 \u0641\u0646\u0627 \u062f\u0631\u06af\u0630\u0631\u06cc\u0645}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0628\u0627 \u0647\u0641\u062a \u0647\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0633\u0627\u0644\u06af\u0627\u0646 \u0633\u0631 \u0628\u0633\u0631\u06cc\u0645}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|'ey <u>d\u016bst</u> biy\u0101 t\u0101 qam-e fard\u0101 na-xor\u012bm}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|v-\u012bn yek-dam-e <u>\u02beomr</u>-r\u0101 qan\u012bmat \u0161omar\u012bm}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|fard\u0101 ke az \u012bn deyr-e fan\u0101 dar-gozar\u012bm}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|b\u0101 <u>haft</u>-he<u>z\u0101r</u>-s\u0101leg\u0101n sar-be-sar-\u012bm}}\n\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | (3.3.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | (5.1.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | (3.3.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | (5.1.13)\n\n:\"O friend, come, let us not eat the sorrow of tomorrow,\n:but count this one moment of life as a blessing.\n:Tomorrow when we pass from this mortal world,\n:we shall be equal with seven-thousand-year-old men.\"\n\n====The wine-seller====\nIn the following example, the [[biceps]] elements at the beginning and end of the line are replaced almost everywhere by a single long syllable:<ref>[https://ganjoor.net/khayyam/robaee/sh167/ Khayyam Roba'i 167] (with recording).</ref>\n \n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u067e\u06cc\u0631\u06cc \u062f\u06cc\u062f\u0645 \u0628\u0647 \u062e\u0627\u0646\u0647\u0654 \u062e\u0645\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06af\u0641\u062a\u0645 \u0646\u06a9\u0646\u06cc \u0632 \u0631\u0641\u062a\u06af\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06af\u0641\u062a\u0627 \u0645\u06cc \u062e\u0648\u0631 \u06a9\u0647 \u0647\u0645\u0686\u0648 \u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0633\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0631\u0641\u062a\u0646\u062f \u0648 \u062e\u0628\u0631 \u0628\u0627\u0632 \u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0627\u0631\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|p\u012br-\u012b d\u012bdam be x\u0101ne-y\u0113 xamm\u0101r-\u012b}} \n:{{lang|fa-Latn|goftam, nakon\u012b ze rafteg\u0101n axb\u0101r-\u012b?}} \n:{{lang|fa-Latn|goft\u0101, mey xor, ke ham\u010do m\u0101 besy\u0101r-\u012b}} \n:{{lang|fa-Latn|raftand o xabar <u>b\u0101z</u> nay\u0101mad b\u0101r-\u012b}}\n\n: \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | (5.1.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | (5.1.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | u \u2013 u \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | (5.1.13)\n: \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 u u \u2013 | \u2013 <u>u u</u> \u2013 | (3.3.13)\n\n:\"I saw an old man in the house of a wine-seller.\n:I said, 'Will you not tell me news of those who have gone?'\n:He said, \"Drink some wine, for many a one like us\n:Has gone, and no news has ever come again.'&thinsp;\"\n\n===Other metres===\n====K\u0101mil====\nAlthough the patterns listed above cover virtually all the poems of the classical period, sometimes other metres are found, used experimentally. The following poem, for example, by the 18th-century poet [[Hatef Esfahani]], is written in the ''[[Kamil (metre)|k\u0101mil]]'' metre, rare in Persian but common in Arabic. It begins as follows:\n\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u0686\u0647 \u0634\u0648\u062f \u0628\u0647 \u0686\u0647\u0631\u0647\u0654 \u0632\u0631\u062f \u0645\u0646 * \u0646\u0638\u0631\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u062e\u062f\u0627 \u06a9\u0646\u06cc}}\n:{{lang|fa|rtl=yes|\u06a9\u0647 \u0627\u06af\u0631 \u06a9\u0646\u06cc \u0647\u0645\u0647 \u062f\u0631\u062f \u0645\u0646 * \u0628\u0647 \u06cc\u06a9\u06cc \u0646\u0638\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u062f\u0648\u0627 \u06a9\u0646\u06cc}}\n\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|\u010de \u0161avad be \u010dehre-ye zard-e man * nazar-\u012b bar\u0101-ye Xod\u0101 kon\u012b}}\n:{{lang|fa-Latn|ke 'agar kon\u012b hame dard-e man * be yek\u012b naz\u0101re dav\u0101 kon\u012b}}\n\n:| uu \u2013 u \u2013 | uu \u2013 u \u2013 || uu \u2013 u \u2013 | uu \u2013 u \u2013 |\n\n:\"If only you could look at my sallow face for the sake of God,\n:since if you did, you would heal all my pain with that single glance!\"\n\nIt is traditionally sung to a melody (''[[dastgah|g\u016b\u0161e]]'') called ''\u010cah\u0101rb\u0101q'', named after the well-known avenue [[Chaharbagh, Isfahan|Chaharbagh]] in [[Isfahan]].<ref>Tsuge, Gen'ichi, (1970) [https://www.jstor.org/stable/849797 \"Rhythmic Aspects of the \u00c2v\u00e2z in Persian Music\"], ''Ethnomusicology'', 14, 2, p. 210</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Bashiri, Iraj (1979). [https://www.academia.edu/7897926/Hafiz_Shirazi_Turk_A_Structuralists_Point_of_View \"Hafiz' Shirazi Turk: A Structuralist's Point of View\"], ''The Muslim World'', LXIX, 979, pp.&nbsp;178\u201397, 248-68. [http://www.angelfire.com/rnb/bashiri/Hafiz/Hafiz.html (alternative link)]\n*Blochmann, Henry (1872). [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_mmUQRv14InIC/page/n3 ''The Prosody of the Persians according to Saifi, Jami, and other Writers'']. Calcutta.\n*Browne, E. G. (1908\u2013). [https://bahai-library.com/browne_literary_history ''A Literary History of Persia''.] Cambridge. (4 volumes)\n*De Blois, Fran\u00e7ois (1994). ''Persian Literature: A Bio-Bibliographical Survey'', vol 5. Royal Asiatic Society.\n*Deo, Ashwini; Kiparsky, Paul (2011). [https://u.osu.edu/deo.13/files//2015/06/DeoKiparsky2011-2fsd6ay.pdf \"Poetries in Contact: Arabic, Persian, and Urdu\"]. In Maria-Kristina Lotman and Mihhail Lotman ed. ''Proceedings of International Conference on Frontiers in Comparative Metrics'', Estonia, pp.&nbsp;147\u2013173.\n*Elwell-Sutton, L.P. (1975). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/4300527 \"The Foundations of Persian Prosody and Metrics\"]. ''Iran'', vol 13. (Available on JSTOR.)\n*Elwell-Sutton, L.P. (1976). [https://books.google.com/books?id=Smy5GE48bWsC ''The Persian Metres'']. Cambridge University Press.\n*Elwell-Sutton, L.P. (1986). [http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/aruz-the-metrical-system \"\u02beAruz\"]. ''Encyclopaedia Iranica''.\n*Farzaad, Masuud (1942). [https://issuu.com/rchakravarti/docs/themetreoftherobaaii_masuudfarzaad_ ''The Metre of the Robaaii.''] Tehran\n*[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/farzad#prettyPhoto Farzaad, M.] (1967). [https://books.google.mw/books?id=diYVAAAAIAAJ&pg=PR3&lpg=PR3&dq=Farzaad,+M.+(1967).+Persian+poetic+meters&source=bl&ots=s2ZS0Qm78q&sig=ACfU3U1hP_LPlDAnhaxGIumWQ93hrLgcdQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjh2sjwv-rlAhXuThUIHU0CBpAQ6AEwAnoECBcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Farzaad%2C%20M.%20(1967).%20Persian%20poetic%20meters&f=false ''Persian poetic meters: a synthetic study.''] Leiden: Brill\n*Hayes, Bruce (1979). [http://linguistics.ucla.edu/people/hayes/papers/HayesRhythmicStructureOfPersianVerse1979.pdf \"The rhythmic structure of Persian verse.\"] ''Edebiyat'' 4, 193\u2013242.\n*Heny, Jeannine Marie (1981). [http://repository.upenn.edu/dissertations/AAI8207974/ ''Rhythmic Elements in Persian Poetry'']. University of Pennsylvania, Ph.D. Dissertation.\n*Hosseini, Seyed Ayat (2014) [http://roa.rutgers.edu/content/article/files/1314_hosseini_1.pdf \"The Phonology and Phonetics of Prosodic Prominence in Persian\"] Ph.D. Dissertation.\n*Mahdavi Mazdeh, Mohsen (2017). [http://www.stonybrook.edu/commcms/nacil/pdfs/abstracts/Mahdavizadeh_NACIL1.pdf \"The quantitative nature of meters in Persian folk songs and pop song lyrics\"]. Paper presented at the ''First North American Conference on Iranian Linguistics'' (NACIL1). Stony Brook, NY. \n*Perry, J. R. (1978). [http://booksandjournals.brillonline.com/content/journals/10.1163/157006478x00138 Review of L. P. Elwell-Sutton ''The Persian Metres''], ''Journal of Arabic Literature'', Volume 9, Issue 1.\n*Thiesen, Finn (1982). [https://issuu.com/rchakravarti/docs/manualclassicalpersianprosody_finnthiesen ''A Manual of Classical Persian Prosody, with chapters on Urdu, Karakhanidic and Ottoman prosody.''] Wiesbaden.\n\n==External links==\nPattern 1\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5lAsRCRapsE&t=44s Opening lines of Ferdowsi's ''Shahnameh''] recited in Persian. 1.1.11\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OcQHSg_YZ6I Saadi's ''Ban\u012b '\u0100dam''] recited in Persian by Amir Ghaseminejad. 1.1.11\n\nPattern 2\n*[http://ganjoor.net/hafez/ghazal/sh3/ Hafez's ''Shirazi Turk''] Persian text, and recitations by Fereidoun Farahanduz, Soheyl Ghassemi, and Mohsen Layle Kuhi. 2.1.16\n*[https://blogs.harvard.edu/sulaymanibnqiddees/2012/11/06/rumi-i-do-not-recognize-myself/ Rumi's ''Neither a Christian nor a Jew''] recited in Persian by Bahman Sharif (text and translation supplied). 2.1.16\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1crLioGCgAs Rumi's ''Ne